Table \ref{tab:ing_changes} shows projected changes in mean seasonal hail days,
and means of daily average hail size, wind speed, and storm-relevant atmospheric
properties, at hail times, in the future compared to historical simulations.
Here we discuss only statistically significant changes. Between epochs, there
were increases in seasonal hail days of 29\% in the Sydney/Canberra region, and
15\% in the Brisbane area. The variability in seasonal hail days was similar
between epochs (Supporting Information Table \ref{SM-tab:frequency}). Mean hail
size increased by \Sexpr{ing_change("Melbourne", "Mean hail")} mm around
Melbourne, Sydney/Canberra, and Brisbane, while maximum hail size, which is more
important for damage potential, increased by \Sexpr{ing_change("Melbourne", "Max
hail")} mm around Melbourne and \Sexpr{ing_change("Sydney/Canberra", "Max
hail")} mm around Sydney/Canberra. Mean wind changes were generally small, with
increases of \Sexpr{ing_change("Perth", "Mean wind")} km h$^{-1}$ around Perth
and \Sexpr{ing_change("Sydney/Canberra", "Mean wind")} km h$^{-1}$ around
Sydney/Canberra. Maximum winds increased slightly in Brisbane and
Sydney/Canberra, and by \Sexpr{ing_change("Melbourne", "Max wind")} km h$^{-1}$
around Melbourne. In every domain there were increases in temperature at 500
hPa, freezing-level and melting-level heights. Convective available potential
energy (CAPE) increased around Adelaide, Brisbane, Melbourne, and
Sydney/Canberra, while changes in lifted index (LI) were more mixed. Convective
inhibition (CIN) strengthened in all domains except Perth, and the lapse rate
slightly increased in Brisbane and Sydney/Canberra. Wind shear changes were
relatively small, indicating that the projections for hail damage potential are
driven more by changes in instability than shear. The extreme value analysis
results for hail size around Melbourne, Perth, Sydney/Canberra, and Kalgoorlie
are supported by increasing convective instability, convective inhibition and
freezing level height, indicating increased updraft strength combined with
increased melting of small hailstones, but survival of large hailstones.
Increases in mean daily hail-proximal wind maxima in Melbourne, Brisbane, and
Sydney/Canberra are supported by increases in CAPE in those domains. The extreme
value analysis showed that the increases in mean in Melbourne and
Sydney/Canberra were accompanied by a narrowing of the distributions of daily
maximum hail-proximal winds (Supplementary Figure \ref{SM-fig:densities_wind}),
which explains why the average hail-proximal wind was projected to increase
while the probability of cross thresholds for damaging winds were projected to
decrease in these domains. In the Brisbane domain there was more of a balance
between modest increases in instability and decreases in wind shear, indicating
that there may be offsetting of changes, leading to no significant change in
damage potential in the EVD analyses. 

