\subsection{Correlations between regions}

We investigate interregional correlations in seasonal hail days to assess
whether resource requirements for responses to hail events may change. There was
co-fluctuation in seasonal hail days between the east-coast domains of
Melbourne, Sydney/Canberra and Brisbane in both historical and future epochs,
with Adelaide significantly correlated with Melbourne and Sydney/Canberra in the
future projections (Supporting Material Figure \ref{SM-fig:correlations}).
Correlations in seasonal mean hail diameter between the Kalgoorlie, Perth,
Melbourne, and Sydney/Canberra domains were stronger in the future projections
than in the historical epoch, while wind correlations between the Perth region
and other south-western domains of Adelaide and Kalgoorlie were evident in the
historical epoch but disappeared in the future projections. Instability was
correlated between Melbourne and Sydney/Canberra domains in both epochs.
Temperature-related parameters showed strong correlations between nearby
domains, such as Kalgoorlie and Perth in the west, which increased in strength
in the projections, and Brisbane and Sydney/Canberra in the east.

\subsection{Historical climatology and comparison with radar}

Our confidence in the results presented above is bolstered by comparisons
between the statistics of the historical period and other data sources. The
climatology of the historical period (Supplementary Table
\ref{SM-tab:frequency}) matched expectations in terms of the relative numbers of
hail days per domain based on a hail proxy \cite{Raupach_npjCAS_2023}. Further,
the climatology is similar to radar records, albeit with slight underestimations
of seasonal hail days in the simulations, and some uncertainty in the radar data
over whether the Brisbane or Sydney/Canberra domain is the most hail-prone
(Supporting Information Table \ref{SM-tab:radar_stats}). The largest
disagreement in seasonal hail days between simulations and radar was for the
Sydney/Canberra domain, in which the simulated seasonal hail days also showed
the largest inter-annual variability (Supplementary Tables
\ref{SM-tab:frequency} and \ref{SM-tab:radar_stats}). There are differences in
the percentages of hail days containing large (50 mm or 100 mm) hail between the
radar data and simulations with radar detecting large hail more often than the
simulations produced it. However, the two datasets agreed on Adelaide and
Sydney/Canberra having the greatest probabilities of producing 100 mm hail, on
days when hail occurred. Overall, given the high uncertainties inherent in both
simulation \cite{Adams-Selin_WF_2019} and radar-detection of hail
\cite{Greco_WF_2024}, we are satisfied with the reliability of our historical
dataset when compared with other data sources.

\section{Conclusions}

We show downscaled regional climate projections of hail size and hail-proximal wind
speed over hail-prone regions of Australia, for SSP2-4.5 in 2080--2099 compared
to a 1989--2009 baseline, with boundary conditions derived from 18 CMIP ensemble
members. The domains included major cities and covered more than 65\% of
Australia's population. Unlike proxy-based studies, our analysis used
convection-permitting modelling that could explicitly simulate storms, and
unlike in pseudo-global warming studies, we used boundary conditions from global
models that include projected changes in both atmospheric thermodynamics and
large-scale circulations.

Between historical and future epochs, overall hail frequency was projected to
increase by 29\% in Sydney/Canberra and 15\% in Brisbane, without significant
changes elsewhere. Average maximum hail size was projected to increase around
Sydney/Canberra, Brisbane, and Melbourne, and average maximum hail-proximal wind
was projected to increase around Brisbane, Melbourne, and Sydney/Canberra.
Changes in extreme value distributions were considered statistically significant
in Melbourne, Perth, and Sydney/Canberra, and for hail size only in Kalgoorlie.
Around Melbourne, Perth, and Sydney/Canberra, maximum hail sizes were projected
to increase while the probability of damaging winds in proximity to hail was
projected to decrease. There were non-significant indications of increased
maximum hail-proximal wind speeds around Adelaide and Kalgoorlie. Increases in
maximum hail size and maximum hail-proximal winds were correlated with increases
in atmospheric instability -- there was generally little projected change in
vertical wind shear except a decrease around Brisbane. Interregional
correlations in seasonal average hail size were projected to strengthen, which
may challenge community resilience and increase resource requirements for repair
after major hail events.

Our projections of increased hail frequency for Sydney/Canberra and indications
of decreases in the other studied domains (other than Brisbane) align with past
trends in hail-prone environments in reanalyses (1979-2021), but the summer
increase in hail frequency we project around Brisbane contradicts with these
past trends \cite{Raupach_npjCAS_2023}. This contradiction, combined with the
possibility we have noted of instability and wind shear changes producing
offsetting effects in the Brisbane area, increases the uncertainty on
projections around Brisbane. Our projections of decreasing hail-proximal
damaging winds around Sydney/Canberra and Melbourne align with
convection-permitting projections that also show decreases in all convective
winds in a similar region \cite{Brown_NHESS_2024}. Our results align with
projections from primarily lapse-rate-based wind proxies \cite{Brown_JGRA_2021},
but contradict with primarily CAPE-based proxies \cite{Brown_JGRA_2021}. For the
broader category of all extreme storms, earlier reanalysis data (1979-2016) show
an increasing trend in thunderstorm environments in Australia's southeast
\cite{Dowdy_CD_2020}. Severe storm environment frequencies in global reanalysis
show non-significant increases in Australia's southwest and along the southeast
coastal fringe, and decreases around Adelaide, agreeing with our hail frequency
results, but have opposite sign to our projections for hail frequency around
Canberra and Kalgoorlie \cite{Taszarek_npjCAS_2021}. Global proxy-based
projections for severe storm environments, made without convection-permitting
models, show increases across Australia on average, with more model and proxy
agreement in Australia's southeast and northwest \cite{Lepore_EF_2021}. 

Several caveats apply to our results. We used instantaneous hourly wind values
which were likely underestimates of maximum gusts. We do not explicitly test
whether the hail simulated in this study is wind-driven, but rather analyze
changes in hail size, and in wind strength in temporal and spatial proximity to
hail occurrence. Our simulations used $\sim$3 km grid spacing, allowing for
well-simulated cold pool properties \cite{Prein_PTRS_2021} but limiting
representation of individual downdrafts \cite{Wang_JGRA_2020} and possibly
underestimating convective wind strengths \cite{ElRafei_WCE_2023}. We considered
only the peak convective season of October to February, yet significant hail
events do occur outside these months \cite{ICA_2024} and seasonal shifts in
hail-prone conditions have been observed \cite{Raupach_npjCAS_2023}. Our results
are based on a single realization of possible future projections, and an
ensemble is needed to build a consensus hazard projection. Future work could
address these caveats, consider bivariate analyses of hail and wind, work to
better understand why severe winds are projected to decrease in some domains,
extend the study to other regions and scenarios, consider changes in exposure
and vulnerability, investigate interregional correlations in more detail, and
further progress process-based understanding of hailstorms and their changes in
a warming world.

